Up for sale is my Burris Euro Diamond Scope model 200916. It is a 3-12x50 with the Ballistic Plex reticle. This was produced to be a top of the line scope for Burris, designed to compete with the high end Euro optics. I have owned many scopes, and this is a very nice piece of glass. One thing I really loved was its performance in low light conditions. It really shined on late night hunts and target shoots, as I was able to make out targets others were not. Another nice thing about this scope is it carried the Burris lifetime warranty, regardless of the owner. If you ever have any problem, Burris will correct it on their dime no questions asked. This was mounted on my LR-308 in a Larue mount, and it performed very well and was always well cared for. The glass was only cleaned with a lens pen, and it was kept covered when not in use. I never had a single problem with it holding zero or not tracking 100%, it was perfectly reliable as a scope should be. The last time I had it out was at an Appleseed event, and it was ringing steel at long range with no problem.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer SP2340 Blue Line/Very Rare
postcontent:
The "Blue Line" Sig Pro is a special line designed for law enforcement that includes three full-capacity magazines and only one grip insert (the thinner/smaller/stippled one). SIGLITE night sights also seem to be common among "Blue Line" Sig Pros. The Sig Pro pistol itself is identical to civilian Sig Pros except for a "Blue Line" crest on the top of the slide, between the rear sight and ejection port, like in the photo below:

Non-LE individuals can purchase and use "Blue Line" Sig Pros. Prior to 09/14/2004, it was common practice for dealers to replace the three LE magazines with (at the time) legal 10-round magazines. However, this is no longer necessary because full-capacity magazines can now be purchased, regardless of any markings that would suggest otherwise. Please check with local and state laws to make sure that you are not in a jurisdiction that has its own ban on full-capacity magazines.

The product codes—as indicated on the sticker attached to the outside of the case—are different that standard Sig Pros, as follows:
The initial "SP" is replaced by "BL" (standing for, you guessed it, "Blue Line")
An additional letter, along with a hyphen to separate it from the previous letter or letters, is added to the product code, specifically "-G," which presumably means "Government"

So, if a standard Sig Pro SP 2340 chambered in .40 Auto with SIGLITE night sights has "SP2340-40-BSS" as its product code, the corresponding "Blue Line" version would thus have "BL2340-40-BSS-G" as its.

This weapon was a department weapon and has been used. It has the marks and scars of such. It functions great and has been taken care of. Being a Sig, it just works.
Options: Factory night sights/3 -12 round magazines that except either .40 cal or .357 Sig/Blueline stamp/factory case. **Has a rail for tact light, but is a rare design that only fits one tact light made** -will not accept normal 1913 rail tact lights. I have this tact light that has ambidextrous controls. But this tact light is separate from advertised price. It would be + $130 with 4 rare batteries - rare military batteries.
The back strap of this weapon has 2 factory choices but I only have the one to answer any questions.
I'm reasonable on this weapon/price, but common sense applies. For sale purposes, cash only, buyer must have purchase permit or cpl. The only trade I would consider would be quality 1911 full size w/night sights/tact rail, or high end EO Tech. Buyer must still have permit/cpl. If you want pics just ask, more than happy to send some, but haven't been able to post them on them here.

location: Near Valley Hills Mall, Hickory / Lenoir, North Carolina
postcontent:
I just bought this rifle a couple of months ago and have never fired it. My wife is squeamish about it because it is an old russian rifle that may have bad mojo from past wars. It was one of three with the hex receiver that the dealer had available. I hand picked it from the others. The rifling is really nice. Before my wife learned the history of these rifles, she encouraged me to buy it because she liked the wood. All numbers match except the bayonet. It comes with the sling, two double ammo pouches, tool and cleaning accessories kit, bayonet, oil can, and 20 rounds of ammo. At this price, I will be in the hole because I have disassembled the gun twice and cleaned the cosmoline out and oiled it up nicely. It's ready to fire. I took the bolt completely apart and was very methodical about getting all of the cosmoline out of every crevice and orifice. This rifle is a nice find and a real piece of history.

Local only. Must have photo ID and CCW or pistol purchase permit.

EOTech's shortest sight yet, the XPS3-0 holographic weapons sight (HWS) is smaller and lighter than other HWS sights yet still provides high-quality visibility in any light condition. The XPS3-0 sports a revolutionary sighting system based on advanced holographic technology. The design works by using laser light to illuminate a holographic pattern embedded in the heads-up display window. When the shooter looks through the window, he or she will see a virtual red image of a reticle pattern projected onto the target plane. Overall, the holographic sight improves target acquisition, boosts accuracy, and increases control over the shooting environment.
The XPS3-0 runs on a single 123 battery and requires at most 2-3/4 inches of rail space. This leaves more room for rear iron sights, magnifiers, or NV mounts. EOTech also eliminated the battery cap and latch and replaced them with a simple tethered O-ring cap to better seal out moisture. Other features include a battery life of up to 600 hours at brightness level 12, fogproof internal optics, water-resistance to 33 feet, and night vision compatibility.

The XPS3-0 projects a holographic red reticle onto the target plane.
